Article [underline]Grayling[/underline]. -
The Grayling is a more
gregarious fish than the
trout but not so much so
as the perch. (text)
[underline]Note[/underline]. Solitary fish in general
or fish that associate [insertion]only[/insertion] during
the time of sexual connexions
have usually more fixed
haunts than gregarious
fish who generally
choose pools of a size &

[page]109||dnp14j107pp|74393166[/page]
[underline]107[/underline]
form fitted for their motion
or food. The pike for instance
or a large trout generally
fixes him self near a [deletion]large[/deletion] [insertion]great[/insertion]
stone or bank or trunk
of a tree to which he
can retire in case of alarm
but this is seldom the case
with [underline]Grayling[/underline] or even with
small trout which often
associate together. The
trout being a fish of prey
& which sometimes destroys
even its own kind is not
likely when large to be
followed by small trout
but the Grayling which is
certainly innocuous to its
own species at least even
when of The largest size
is often followed by
smaller ones. |_ It is very
difficult to explain the

[page]110||dnp14j108pp|74393167[/page]
cause of the gregarious
associations of fish
but it is probably gener
=ally connected with the
search[deletion]ing[/deletion] [insertion]after[/insertion] their food & in
some cases perhaps
nourishment is supplied
to water by fish . I [deletion]have[/deletion]
observed [insertion]in 1828[/insertion] in a branch of
the Save at Lustthal
near Laibach a young
Sturgeon which was
preserved as a curiosity
having been brought there
from the Danube. it was
always surrounded by
great numbers of the
[deletion]Eider[/deletion] [insertion]ida[/insertion] carp or breitfisch
which seemed to have
great satisfaction in
touching its skin in
passing over it & [unclear]there[/unclear]

[page]111||dnp14j109pp|74393168[/page]
109
were likewise some grayling
which [deletion]seemed[/deletion] [insertion]appeared[/insertion] to cultivate
the same kind of acquain[deletion]t[/deletion]
=tance. The skin of this
fish is always covered
with a [deletion][unclear]dead[/unclear][/deletion] [insertion]thick[/insertion] slime & it is
not I think improbable
that the other fish [unclear]derive[/unclear]
nourishment from it.
The ancients had many
singular ideas respecting
the fondness or antipathies
of certain species of fish
with respect to each other
They believed that there was
a strong antipathy beteen
the Muraena & the Congor
I have seen in the fish market
at Rome certainly two distinct
Species of Congors & I once
opened a large Muraena. ( M.
Helena) which contained in its
stomach a hook that had
tance. The skin of this

[page]112||dnp14j110pp|74393169[/page]
been baited with a piece
of common eel. These
fishes being all extremely
rapacious & feeding in
the same haunts I have
no doubt destroy each
other whenever they can
The identity of the vari.
eties of fish known
to the ancients is a
curious subject of
scientific enquiry -
The ancient Romans
seem to have preserved
their fish & to have pre.
pared them for the pur.
-poses of the table
with much greater
care than the modern
epicureans of Eurpoe

[page]113||dnp14j111pp|74393170[/page]
111
The Muraena is now a
rare fish in the roman
market & is not much
esteemed by the italians
spotted like a snake
& slimy like an eel
it seems to require some
particular sauce or some
peculiar coating to give
it that character
which the Romans of
the Time of Augustus
attributed to it of being
the most delicate of
Sea fishes. I have
eaten it boiled & fried
in paper & cannot
say that it struck me
as being equal to a
good eel of the Skerries
It was less fat & I

[page]114||dnp14j112pp|74393171[/page]
should think less lusci
=ous & cloying as food
